question:
In a digital archiving system, a “record ID” is any three-digit number (other than a fixed three-digit number \(n\)). The system can form a long archive code by concatenating the same record ID repeatedly. Determine the three-digit number \(n\) such that, for every possible three-digit record ID different from \(n\), both of the following concatenated archive codes are divisible by \(n\):

- the code formed by writing the ID \(10^{2024}\) times in a row;
- the code formed by writing the ID \(10^{2024}+2\) times in a row.
